In article <2hovun$f0u@news.kth.se>,
Urban Koistinen <md85-epi@hemul.nada.kth.se> wrote:
>In <2hmliuINNjqo@bhars12c.bnr.co.uk> wolfe@bnr.co.uk (Ian Woollard) writes:
>
>>I would assume that all practical RSA programs pad out the message
>>with (I would hope random bits) upto the full length...
>
>I think pgp does not do this but pad with all ones or zeroes instead.
>But then again, there is at least 128 random bits (the IDEA key).

PGP pads with random bits.  It uses all 1's for signatures (you want
signatures to be hard to generate by accident, so you want as much structure
as possible), but random bits for keys. There are some fixed bits, but
not too many.
